1) Internal structure of hashMap

HashMap is based on :
    * Array of buckets
    * Each bucket initially stores a linked list
    * From java 8 Onwards , if collisions increase, linked List - > Red-Black Tree

2) How hashMap stores key-values pair

    step 1 : HashMap calculates the hash using :
                hash = key.hasCode();

    Step 2 : Maps hash to bucket index
                index = hash % arrayLength

    step 3 : If no element --> insert node
                if element present --> collision handling happens


3) Collision handling
    HashMap handles collisions using :
        Before java 8
            Chaining using Linked List
        After java 8
            linked list --> Balanced Red-black Tree
            (Only when bucket has 8 or more nodes )

            This improves performance from
            O(n) --> O(log n)

4) Rehashing
    when HashMap reaches its threshold(capacity * load factor), it double the array size and rearranges entries

    initial capacity = 16
    load factor =0.75
    threshold = 16*0.75 =12

    when size becomes 12, HashMap expands --> capacity 32

5) Why load factor 0.75?

    it is a balance between:
      * space(memory)
      * Time (Search/insert performance)

Higher load factor = more collisions = slower
lower load factor = more space wasted

6) Treefication Threshold
    If collisions exceed TREEIFY_THRESHOLD = 8,
    Linked list --> Red-Black Tree
    De-treeify when size drop below UNTREEIFY_THRESHOLD = 6.


